<br>
A hissed whisper slipped from the shadows immediately behind Lady Larisian, cutting straight into her ear and startling her.<br>
<br>
&quot;When it comes, the landscape listens,<br>
&quot;Shadows hold their breath;<br>
&quot;When it goes, 't is like the distance<br>
&quot;On the look of death.&quot;<br>
<br>
Larisian's eyes narrowed suspiciously.  She held motionless, tense, waiting to respond to any act threatening her self - an act which she now anticipated nervously.  Yet the very idea that she should suddenly be threatened in her own hall...  The guards posted at the door lowered their weapons and began to approach.<br>
<br>
Fearing the immediacy of her stalker, Larisian lifted her hand slightly and the guards stood still.  &quot;What do you want?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh dear, you folks are so jittery.&quot;  A tittering giggle filled the guildhall - a giggle Larisian instantly recognized.  Her muscles released with the soft breath that crept from her mouth.  Her mouth turned quickly to a warm smile.<br>
<br>
&quot;I only came to return this.&quot;  Mumsley slipped from behind her....so odd that nobody had seen him standing there before.  He held out a small broach, glistening gold with a large, glittering emerald.  &quot;I believe that it...&quot;  Mumsley coughed, &quot;...fell...to the cold vellium flagstones when we embraced in greeting last time we met in the new lands.  I shouldn't like those silly dwarves in Thurgadin to have such a thing, so naturally I grabbed it to return to you.&quot;<br>
<br>
Larisian responded with sarcasm, &quot;Naturally--&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Well, that's all,&quot;  Mumsley turned to leave.  Larisian lifted her hand to wave, only to find that suddenly he was gone.<br>
<br>
A voice crept from behind her again.  She couldn't help but tense up in memory of the startle she had been given earlier.  &quot;Say....I couldn't help but overhear.  I don't like to remember it, but I have spent some time imprisoned in Oggok.  I made my escape through....certain....underground passages beneath the city.<br>
<br>
&quot;The purpose of those passages is too terrible to relate, but suffice it to say that the extreme difficulty with which I extricated myself from there gives me a long studied familiarity with every twist and turn of every passageway.  They are quite extensive and I'd wager that I could find my way to almost anywhere in the city above, should such come to necessity.<br>
<br>
&quot;You have but to ask....&quot;<br>
<br>
The sounds of a merry mandolin playing a jig drifted through the hall, gradually receding to the far doors and out into the cold, dark night.<br>
