Forseen Shadows<br>
<br>
The lost and confused knight stood alone on the plane that was dotted with the mangled corpses of fighters from which streams of blood trickled. Ariakane pivited slowly as he observed the battle site...small fires were scattered, creating a smog environment as the dense foilage barely let the smoke free. The sun had set and only faint lights from a nearby camp could be seen in the distants and of course the nearby fires. The many corpses were spread all around, each with its own special and unique position, a result from their struggle. There was no sign of life, save for Ariakane's. His eyes scanned the scene and stopped on a way too familiar set of armor that layed sprawled next to a slain wood elf. Ariakane made his way and hovered over the corpse, looking down at the recognizable set of Darkforge Armor that was customly made to fit on the knight. What caught Ariakane's attention was the dragon that had been scrawled into the pauldrons of the armor.<br>
<br>
&quot;Tagnik'zul,&quot; he whispered softly.<br>
<br>
Ariakane removed his gauntlet, bent down, and touched the stagnant blood that had collected in the gaping wound of the fallen soldier's back. It was warm. He then turned the corpse upwards to look for anyother signs of possible life...there were none. The knight layed there lifelesly, staring into the canopy of the forest through the eye slits of his helmet. Ariakane continued to focus on this one knight and then noticed the emblem etched into the chestplate of the armor.<br>
<br>
&quot;Thedar d'Tagnik'zul,&quot; he said aloud. He rose to his feet and whispered, &quot; I must report this to the Head Of-,&quot; his words were haulted as he stood in shock. The helmet that was on the corpse was now missing and exposed the face of the knight...it was Ariakane's. He stared at the face in fear and watched as it shape-shifted...<br>
<br>
&quot;Ariakane! Wakie wakiez!&quot;<br>
<br>
Ariakane awoke suprisedly to find the Orkhalla's face projected into his vision. Rukkas grinned as he enjoyed startling his warrior, gaining pleasure like he always did from simple moments like this.<br>
<br>
&quot;What happened?&quot; Ariakane managed to speak, groaning while he stretched. The faded lights of the forest shined into the window, it was morning. Ariakane pulled his feet out of the bed and placed them on the floor.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yus throwin ups las nitez. Yus mus hab thron up da previus nites dinnur as well! Hehehar!&quot; the ogre exclaimed. &quot;Uhparentleez yus don like da way Frakk cooks da fishees!! Mmmmm dat sauz wuz gud...&quot;<br>
<br>
Ariakane's stomached churned as he recalled the fish prepared by Frakk.<br>
<br>
&quot;Weez still gots mor if yus tink yus can handel it!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;No thanks, perhaps Lady Lilya will be kind enough to prepare me breakfast.&quot;<br>
<br>
There was no response from Rukkas. He was obviously still thinking of last night's dinner.The ogre stared at the wall as pools of saliva began to amass in his mouth. Ariakane gave him a sharp kick to keep the ogre from overflowing in front oh him.<br>
<br>
&quot;Mez sa-,&quot; Rukkas paused to swallow his fluids, &quot;Meez sawwy...whachu say?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;My meal,&quot; Ariakane responded, &quot;I am going to ask Lady Lilya to -&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;She notz heer nowz,&quot; Rukkas addes sharply.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh&quot; Ariakane's stomach once again began to rumble, as if it were begging him not to resort to Frakk's fish. &quot;Where is she?&quot; he asked.<br>
<br>
&quot;Culd be anywhere,&quot; Rukkas stated. &quot;Almos all da Elders of da tribe gon on pursunal bizness,&quot; the ogre concluded sadly.<br>
<br>
&quot;Well then...I guess I will go and make some breakfast and see how the day progresses.&quot; Ariakane made his way to the kitchen and called out to Rukkas, &quot;Want anything?!&quot; Rukkas happily jumped to his feet and hastily joined Ariakane in the kitchen.<br>
<br>
The meal was finished with Ariakane washing up and Rukkas licking the remaining sauces in his bowl with Ariakane's back to him. Ariakane sneaked a peek and smiled to himself thinking of how much of a child his leader was. But it was nothing he worried about for he enjoyed it, and he knew when the time came, he could always count on Rukkas to watch his back. Ariakane turned around, walked back to the table and discovered the Halfling slaves Ican and Feudil snickering at Rukkas, apparently at his 'table manners'. Ariakane scowled them before they dashed off to complete their tedious chores around the Severed Souls Hall. Rukkas patted his mouth with his cloth napkin like a child trying to act elegant and proper, but the fact that his meal was all over his face and table really ruined the effort.<br>
