<br>
Ariakane chuckled at the ogre.<br>
<br>
&quot;You missed a small bit...right...there,&quot; Ariakane told him while pointing at the side of his mouth. Rukkas extended his tongue out and swiped the bits of sauce near his mouth.<br>
<br>
&quot;Gotz it?&quot; Rukkas asked. Ariakane stared at Rukkas's sauce-covered face, laughing inside, keeping it hidden from Rukkas.<br>
<br>
Ariakane smiled, &quot;Yes Orkhalla, now clean up your bowl while I go check in with the remaining Souls.&quot; Rukkas nodded as he inhaled a jug of Bog Juice.<br>
<br>
Ariakane stepped out of the kitchen and glanced down the corridors, noticing it's vacancy. The hallway was dimly lit with a few candles lining the walls, and the sunlight that made its way from the Hall entrance. <br>
<br>
Ariakane began to walk towards the Souls Den Room when he heard a loud thump followed immediately by loud crashes.<br>
<br>
&quot;The kitchen.....Rukkas!&quot; Ariakane exclaimed as he quickly removed the dagger from his belt and proceeded to the kitchen. <br>
<br>
He reached the doorway and began to step in when he was greeted with an enormous growl from Rukkas that sent him to the ground. Feudil and Ican followed, tumbling into the wall outside the kitchen door.Ican scrambled to his feet and hurried to Feudil. He attempted to pick Feudil to his feet only to discover that he had been knocked unconscious. The top of Feudil's dripped with blood. <br>
<br>
Ican looked to Ariakane. He was dazed and phased out. He then dragged Feudil around the corner hastefully and began to tear and scratch at the collar that had been bound to his neck by the Souls.<br>
<br>
The collar had been cast upon by the Elders of the Severed Souls. It locked the channeling capabilities of its wearer. But the Souls were slightly merciful as they allowed the halflings to cast freely in their private rooms. They did however, seal all possible portals able to be summoned in that area.<br>
<br>
Ican continued to struggle with the collar strapped to his neck. He felt a small tear in the collar along the buckle as he lashed at it vigorously. He dug his nail into the slit as he successively ripped the collar off his neck. He felt a cool breeze course through his body as the ability to channel returned to him. Ican began to chant a prayer to Mother Tunare, as he began to restore consciousness to Feudil.<br>
<br>
Rukkas walked out of the kitchen, looking down the hallway, searching for the halfling slaves. He discovered Ariakane phased out on the ground, his head bobbing side to side, in a state of semi-consciousness...<br>
<br>
Ariakane found himself standing in the familiar vacant forest. He realized where he was...the battle site. He quickly turned around to find nothing. All the bodies that were once blotted all over the place, were gone. The fires were dying out and much of the smoke had escaped the forest.<br>
<br>
Ariakane walked around as he observed the mysterious environment that he had once again been brought to. He began to descend down a slope as he tripped over an exposed tree root. He tumbled down the slope, through bushes, vines, and more roots before he crashed into a large, solid object. He then picked himself up and discovered what laid before his feet. Rakkas's body.<br>
<br>
It appeared to have been mutilated. The exposed skin of the ogre had been singed by pelts of fire and blankets of frost. His armor had been so badly beaten with deformity, that the original texture and shape of it could never be figured. It was apparent that he had been involved in a slaughtering offensive, but from who or what? The wide and gaping wounds were everywhere on his body. The blood that was released from the cuts looked as if they blended with Rakkas's Sentient Armor. But Ariakane soon realized as he looked Rakkas up and down, that the armor did not blend in with the blood, but had been covered with a dry coat of Rakkas's own blood.<br>
<br>
Ariakane looked up to discover yet another surprise.<br>
<br>
&quot;Rukkas...,&quot; Ariakane sadly whispered to himself. He hurried over to the bulk in the Totemic Armor, still grasping to his spear. His body was less severed than his brother's.<br>
<br>
Ariakane began to chant a prayer, but was interrupted as the sound of rustling brush sent Ariakane's hand to his side to find nothing. The dark elf cursed under his breath before he chanted the words to a spell and was washed away with shadows.<br>
<br>
Two figures stepped out of the faint mist that covered the forest floor. One of them was noticeably a gigantic barbarian who possessed the ability to channel the mana of shamans. He carried skulls, legs, tongues, and many other undesirables to common folk, all over him. The stench that he emitted was a warm mixture of fluids and gland sacs from creatures.<br>
<br>
Ariakane covered his nose and began to appreciate the fact that the tribal shamans in his guild ate most of the spell components they gathered instead of carrying them around.<br>
<br>
The other figure was one of a male, a sleek, well shaped, and defined half-elven. He stood with a great stature as he appeared to be reconning the area. His head slowly turned toward Ariakane's position and his mouth stretched to a soft smirk.<br>
<br>
Ariakane felt the icy stare pierce his soul as they caught eachother's glance. He had somehow discovered Ariakane among the shadows. Ariakane stared at the elf as he called out and motioned towards his position with his drawn sword...<br>
<br>
Nothing moved in the hall. It was quiet as ever and Ariakane could only remember vague events from his 'dream'. He leaned his head forward as he regained total consciousness. He looked down each way of the hall and found nothing peculiar at all. He then laid his head against the wall, closed his eyes, and released a heavy sigh.<br>
